706	assistant	{"id": "840a4804-9ff2-40fa-bf60-dab4d40125c0", "object": "completion", "created": 1713686930, "model": "private-gpt", "choices": [{"finish_reason": "stop", "delta": null, "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": "Remittance services play a crucial role in the global economy, allowing individuals and businesses to transfer funds across borders for various purposes such as supporting family members, paying for goods and services, and investing in foreign markets. However, these services can also be misused for money laundering and financing terrorism, making it essential for financial institutions and regulatory agencies to implement robust anti-money laundering (AML) and combating the financing of terrorism (CFT) measures.\\n\\nTo mitigate the risks associated with remittance transactions, banks and other financial institutions should establish a comprehensive AML/CFT program that includes customer due diligence, transaction monitoring, and risk assessment. Some key elements of an effective program include:\\n\\n1. Customer identification and verification: Financial institutions should verify the identity of their customers and the beneficiaries of remittance transactions, using reliable and independent sources of information. This may include obtaining and verifying personal information such as name, address, date of birth, and government-issued identification documents.\\n\\n2. Transaction monitoring: Financial institutions should monitor remittance transactions for suspicious activity, such as unusual patterns, large transactions, or transactions involving high-risk jurisdictions. This can be done through automated systems that analyze transaction data and generate alerts for further investigation when necessary.\\n\\n3. Risk assessment: Financial institutions should regularly assess and update their risk profiles, taking into account factors such as the types of products and services offered, the geographic locations of customers and counterparties, and the potential for money laundering and terrorist financing in specific industries or sectors.\\n\\n4. Staff training and awareness: Financial institutions should provide ongoing training and education for employees on AML/CFT policies and procedures, as well as the risks associated with remittance transactions and how to identify and report suspicious activity.\\n\\n5. Cooperation with regulatory agencies: Financial institutions should maintain open lines of communication with regulatory agencies and be prepared to provide information and assistance in investigations related to money laundering and terrorist financing.\\n\\nBy implementing these measures, financial institutions can help mitigate the risks associated with remittance transactions and contribute to a safer and more transparent global financial system."}, "sources": [{"object": "context.chunk", "score": 0.6950412968817871, "document": {"object": "ingest.document", "doc_id": "3550335a-9fe0-4a8b-ab6c-28dc62c41d37", "doc_metadata": {"window": "The concerned departments/ \\nfunctions are free to build their own additional triggers or modify the parameters of the \\nbelow mentioned triggers as per their discretion so as to strengthen the AML/CFT \\nprogram of the Bank. \\n 4.3.1 Remittance transactions related \\nFollowing triggers shall assist the Bank to identify such transactions. \\n 1.  Provide special attention where remittance in smaller volume or the \\npurpose of remittance received is not clear to the receiver: \\na. a number of transactions is made by the same counter-party (sender) \\nin amounts less than NPR 0.1 million to multiple customers \\n \\nb. there is high frequency of remittance received in an account in a \\nmonth in amount less than NPR 0.1 million \\n \\nc. Customer does not appear to know the sender of fund and its \\nintended purpose for remittance above NPR 1 million. \\n \\n 2.  Closely examine the any transaction in which the nature, size or \\nfrequency appears unusual where: \\na. the remittance received in excess of NPR 0.1 million is immediately \\nwithdrawn in cash. \\n \\n b. the remittance received is transferred to multiple accounts within the \\nBank or to other banks through the use of digital channels. \\n \\n", "original_text": "Provide special attention where remittance in smaller volume or the \\npurpose of remittance received is not clear to the receiver: \\na. a number of transactions is made by the same counter-party (sender) \\nin amounts less than NPR 0.1 million to multiple customers \\n \\nb. there is high frequency of remittance received in an account in a \\nmonth in amount less than NPR 0.1 million \\n \\nc. Customer does not appear to know the sender of fund and its \\nintended purpose for remittance above NPR 1 million. \\n \\n", "page_label": "34", "file_name": "AML CFT Guideline 2023 (2).pdf", "doc_id": "3550335a-9fe0-4a8b-ab6c-28dc62c41d37"}}, "text": "The concerned departments/ \\nfunctions are free to build their own additional triggers or modify the parameters of the \\nbelow mentioned triggers as per their discretion so as to strengthen the AML/CFT \\nprogram of the Bank. \\n 4.3.1 Remittance transactions related \\nFollowing triggers shall assist the Bank to identify such transactions. \\n 1.  Provide special attention where remittance in smaller volume or the \\npurpose of remittance received is not clear to the receiver: \\na. a number of transactions is made by the same counter-party (sender) \\nin amounts less than NPR 0.1 million to multiple customers \\n \\nb. there is high frequency of remittance received in an account in a \\nmonth in amount less than NPR 0.1 million \\n \\nc. Customer does not appear to know the sender of fund and its \\nintended purpose for remittance above NPR 1 million. \\n \\n 2.  Closely examine the any transaction in which the nature, size or \\nfrequency appears unusual where: \\na. the remittance received in excess of NPR 0.1 million is immediately \\nwithdrawn in cash. \\n \\n b. the remittance received is transferred to multiple accounts within the \\nBank or to other banks through the use of digital channels. \\n \\n", "previous_texts": null, "next_texts": null}, {"object": "context.chunk", "score": 0.6929846034836663, "document": {"object": "ingest.document", "doc_id": "b6ec1547-4ed9-4aaf-b87a-1ee8390ccbc4", "doc_metadata": {"window": "Regulatory Agency \\nA government entity \\nresponsible for supervising \\nand overseeing one or more \\ncategories of financial \\ninstitutions.  The agency \\ngenerally has authority to \\nissue regulations, to conduct \\nexaminations, to impose fines \\nand penalties, to curtail \\nactivities and, sometimes, to \\nterminate charters of \\ninstitutions under its \\njurisdiction. \\n Related persons \\nProprietor, partners, board of \\ndirectors, executive / \\nmanagement committee \\nmembers, chief executive \\nofficer, and account operators \\nof a firm, company and trust \\nas appropriate.  Remittance Services \\nRemittance services are \\nbusinesses that receive cash \\nor other funds that they \\ntransfer through the banking \\nsystem to another account. \\n The account is held by an \\nassociated company in a \\nforeign jurisdiction where the \\nmoney is made available to \\nthe ultimate recipient. \\n Residual risk \\nThis is the assessed ML/TF \\nrisk after AML/CFT controls \\nand measures have been put \\nin place. \\n \\n Respondent Bank \\nA bank for which another \\nfinancial institution \\nestablishes, maintains, \\nadministers or manages a \\ncorrespondent account. \\n", "original_text": "Remittance Services \\nRemittance services are \\nbusinesses that receive cash \\nor other funds that they \\ntransfer through the banking \\nsystem to another account. \\n", "page_label": "59", "file_name": "AML CFT Guideline 2023 (2).pdf", "doc_id": "b6ec1547-4ed9-4aaf-b87a-1ee8390ccbc4"}}, "text": "Regulatory Agency \\nA government entity \\nresponsible for supervising \\nand overseeing 