804	assistant	{"id": "8dd59183-f181-4bb6-9ab3-9db8551ad529", "object": "completion", "created": 1713689549, "model": "private-gpt", "choices": [{"finish_reason": "stop", "delta": null, "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": "Working capital guidelines refer to the financial management practices that help a business maintain a healthy balance between its current assets and current liabilities. These guidelines are essential for ensuring the smooth operation of a business by providing a framework for managing cash flow, inventory, accounts receivable, and accounts payable. Here are some key aspects of working capital guidelines:\\n\\n1. Maintain a positive working capital ratio: A positive working capital ratio indicates that a company has more current assets than current liabilities. This ratio should be maintained to ensure that the business has enough cash to meet its short-term obligations.\\n\\n2. Monitor inventory levels: Excessive inventory can tie up cash and resources, while insufficient inventory can lead to lost sales opportunities. Working capital guidelines should include inventory management practices to ensure an optimal balance between stock levels and cash flow.\\n\\n3. Manage accounts receivable: Unpaid invoices can also strain cash flow. Working capital guidelines should include policies for prompt invoicing, credit checks on customers, and timely follow-up on overdue payments.\\n\\n4. Manage accounts payable: Delaying payments to suppliers can help improve cash flow in the short term, but it can also damage business relationships and lead to penalties. Working capital guidelines should include a balance between paying suppliers promptly and maximizing cash flow.\\n\\n5. Forecast cash flow: Accurate cash flow forecasting is essential for managing working capital effectively. Working capital guidelines should include processes for regularly forecasting cash inflows and outflows to identify potential cash shortfalls or surpluses.\\n\\n6. Monitor financial performance: Regularly monitoring key financial metrics such as days sales outstanding (DSO), days inventory outstanding (DIO), and days payable outstanding (DPO) can help identify areas for improvement in working capital management.\\n\\n7. Adjust guidelines as needed: Working capital guidelines should be flexible enough to adapt to changing business conditions. Regularly reviewing and updating these guidelines based on market trends, customer demands, and business growth can help ensure their effectiveness.\\n\\nBy following these working capital guidelines, businesses can maintain a healthy balance between their current assets and liabilities, ensuring a stable cash flow and the ability to meet short-term obligations."}, "sources": [{"object": "context.chunk", "score": 0.6671502245119011, "document": {"object": "ingest.document", "doc_id": "698d2519-66ff-4eb7-af80-8ae7d427243e", "doc_metadata": {"window": "4 check and Review... 31\\nChapter ll: Cash, Vault Operations and Transaction Procedures - Operations\\nManua1.,.................  ...................................32\\n1 General Guide|ines................. .323.4\\n3.4.1\\n3.4.2\\n3.5\\n3.6\\n3.7\\n3.8\\n2.5.6\\n2.6\\n2.6.7\\n) a7\\n2.6.3\\n2.6.4\\n2.6.s\\n2.6.6\\n2.7\\n2.7.L\\n2.8\\n2,8.7\\n2.8.2 Cheque Transfer...\\nCash Payment against Cheque......\\nGood for Payment Cheque...........\\nDishonor of cheque...\\nCheque Return Reason..................Payment of lnterest and Principa1................\\nPayment of lnterest...\\nPayment of Principal..\\nRenewal of Fixed Oeposit.............................\\nPremature Withdrawal of Fixed Deposit......\\nlssuance of Duplicate Fixed Deposit Receipt\\nStorage of Stock of Fixed Deposit Receipt....\\nCash Transfer for Evening and Holiday Counters..........................\\nMovement of cash outside the Branch Premises..................,,..\\nGeneral Provisions.,...\\n lnter-Branch Cash Transfer..............................\\nlnter-Bank Cash Transfer......