 of credit: A letter of credit is a financial instrument issued by a bank, guaranteeing that the borrower will receive payment if certain conditions are met. The borrower can offer letters of credit as security for a loan.\\n8. Stock or shares: Businesses with publicly traded stock can offer their shares as security for a loan, with the lender selling the shares if necessary to recover the loan amount.\\n\\nIt's essential for borrowers to carefully consider the risks associated with offering security for a business loan, as failure to repay the loan could result in the loss of valuable assets. Borrowers should also ensure that they"}, "sources": [{"object": "context.chunk", "score": 0.6669850026079196, "document": {"object": "ingest.document", "doc_id": "cf5c8a45-222d-49fb-8f9d-f1a1cba3eedc", "doc_metadata": {"window": "j. Loose Cheque: loose cheque is a .ounter cheque issued to the account holders of the bank whh the\\nfacility ofwithdrawlng funds ln the absence of chcquebooks and debit cards.\\n 1.9 Stop Payment: An inskuction hade for stopping payment against cheque at the request o[account holder\\n1.12 Caih (rver/ Shon: Excessof physlcalca5h overthe book balance4s C.sh\\nlance is Cash Shon.1.10 Good ior Paymem Chequa: lt is an endoBement of a cheque by the bank at the aequest ofthe customer for\\nSuaranteeing conflrmed payment agalnst s uch cheque.  The cheque ir drawn by the customer againsl his/her\\nown account with the bank to which the bank adds lts certification/endocemenl.  Such\\ncertlflcation/endorsement guarantees thatthe bank holdsfunds to cover the cheque and willeffect payment\\nupon presentation of the cheque,\\n1.11 OormantAccount: Status ofan accot,lnt which indicatethat th\\u20acre was no customerinitiated transaction takinS\\nplace in the account for el leart within the p\\u20acnod of lastlhree yea6 in case ofsavinF accounts and lasl six\\nmonths in case of current and call accounts.  The account is rertricted for any kind ofcunomer induced de